    {
      "id": "7402fb8fbfe5c61769c356c2b067155b58b6e609",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2020-03-05 20:06:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt should be pointed out this was done to work around a order issue on ARM / Power8 platforms. As you pointed out to me we should mention Linux Commit 2f073848c3cc which addressed this. I will need to test this on Power8 to make their is no regression.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "dfba948d4a3279e36cd8f554e6e69e1678b48169",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2020-03-05 23:26:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nFair enough.\nAs I mentioned separately, I suspect the arm/power8 problem was most likely a compiler bug, though it is not possible to be sure without lots of details.\nAs INIT_LIST_HEAD_RCU is documented as being for cases where the list_head might be concurrently read by another thread, and as that was not there case where it was used in lustre, that usage was arguably wrong.\nI suspect a better approach to fixing the bug would have been to insert a barrier() call after the initialization, along with a comment explaining why it was needed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2611986cec7e417b84fd41a002b6942ac7a92f0a",
      "author": {
